title: NA
comments:
432


In The Inner Reaches Of Outer Space, Joseph Campbell discusses the similarity between the Babylonian and Genesis flood stories. In the Babylonian story, there were ten kings who lived very long lives from the creation to the time of the flood -- a period of time given as 432,000 years. Zecharia Sitchin reckons the time frame to be 445,000 years ago, with the flood pegged at 13,000 years ago. [1] (Do the math.)

In the Biblical account, there were ten patriarchs between Adam and Noah (aka The Adam's Family), who also lived long lives. The total years -- adjusting for the massive overlap in their lives, add up to 1,656. In that number of years, there are 86,400 weeks, or exactly twice 43,200. Curiously, the number of seconds in a 24 hour day is 86,400.

To reconcile taking half of 86,400 to obtain 43,200, one should note the ancient tradition of seeing a cycle as one half waning and one half waxing (as in the lunar cycle). The day thus has 24 hours, or 2 sets of 12 hours -- 12 hours of a waxing sun, followed by 12 hours of a waning sun. 12 is, in fact, considered the celestial holy number (7 being the down-to-earth holy number). Additionally, in Revelation 12, the woman with child has a crown of 12 stars. The New Jerusalem has 12 gates, angels and pearls. And the symbol of the Heart chakra is a 12-petal Lotus Flower . John Mitchell, author of City Of Revelation, shows a diagram of the New Jerusalem Plan, based on St. John’s vision. It has 12 circles in a ring, with a 12-pointed star inside, formed by four overlapping triangles. (The Zodiac is often depicted in a similar way). If you take the circles to be 360 degrees each, and multiplies by the number of circles, the total equals 4,320.

Hosemann was born in Vicksburg in western Mississippi. He received his Bachelor of Business Administration degree in 1969 from the University of Notre Dame in South Bend, Indiana. In 1972, he earned his Juris Doctor from the University of Mississippi School of Law in Oxford, Mississippi. In 1973, he obtained specialization in Taxation at New York University. Hosemann currently lives in the capital city of Jackson, where he is a partner with Phelps Dunbar LLP.[1]

Secretary of State
In the general election on November 6, 2007, Hosemann defeated the Democrat Robert Smith in the race for Secretary of State.[2] In the Republican primary election on August 7, 2007, Hosemann received 54 percent of the vote, defeating former mayor of Columbus Jeffrey Rupp and State Representative Mike Lott of Petal. He took office in January 2008, succeeding Democrat Eric Clark. During the campaign, he took advantage of his unusual name in order to gain name recognition. A series of commercials showed an elderly woman talking about the good things he would do as Secretary of State, meanwhile forgetting his name as he tried to correct her. She typically used similar names such as Gilbert, Albert, Philbert, Dilbert, and Herbert. Since then, various public service messages, such as a reminder to go vote during election season, have included this format, the woman talking about the importance of voting, then mispronouncing Hosemann's name, then Hosemann correcting her and continuing the reminder.

My dear Madhava,

Your ever well-wisher,
A.C. Bhaktivedanta Swami

name: Anonymous
title: Do not go blackpilled even into this night
comments: What is your personal identity in the wake of all that has happened? Do you ever stop to think about what has come of the bloodlines once regarded as blue blood? We are the royalty of ages past, now only remember in the form only we have yet - we are the ones made warriors in our own homes, we are the ones whose every meal has been made a war ration, even if it is all a feast - and unjustly. We are the heirs, whose every action, in word thought and deed now matter, whereas it never had before, and we are not so prepared. We are unknown, even to eachother, and to our own families, who we've seen the joy and home leave out of, gradually, mournfully. Almost all joy has left our world, almost all security. We numb instead of please - and as far as words or sentiments go, we've lost the ability even to tell of a problem long ago.. but we remember, even if there is fault. We are the walking monuments of the past, even if we tear down our walls, old and ornate as they are, and replace them with.. (…) - and we don't want to be. This is how we are. How I am, anyway. I don't know about you, and I don't know how you feel, but it still feels like news to me, this ancient thing, this ancient peace, that it seems only me alone has found, in every thorn, every petal, every old stone wall and dark, candle lit memory from the homeland - it still pains me. It still beckons me. No, I don't know about you, but I know I keep looking at those thorns, those gardens, those graveyards, those old towns, not because of any stone of tree in particular, but because there was something there. There was always someone there. Not too long ago…

name: Anonymous
title: Why I'm proud of COVID-19, and Wish it well.
comments:
At first, the R0 number of 4.08 scared me. In fact, I had an existential crisis. The Los Alamos National Laboratory manuscript pointed towards R0 as 6.6, and University of Georgia and Kyoto University as 7.0. These R0 values are impressive, and deserve respect. Smallpox, for example, had a roughly 6-7 R0 value and decimated the Native American population with a 25-50% mortality rate. 

HMMP you say - 50% mortality rate is far higher than COVID-19. Yes, with hospitalization, COVID-19 has a 5-15% mortality rate, according to multiple reports, including the Chinese CDC. This is fine, you say - but when the critical illness rate of as high as 25%, and a lack of "self healing", and more dangerous with subsequent infections makes COVID-19 a respectable virus. In fact, with the 14-24 day asymptomatic incubation period, COVID-19 will give Smallpox a run for its money. The 1918 Spanish Flu is no where near as potent as COVID-19. 

Even in confined quarters, the 1918 Spanish Flu had a mere 4.0 R0, and just a 4 day incubation period. 

One would be fortunate should this virus mutate into one as "mild" as the 1918 Spanish Flu. 

Why do I wish COVID-19 well? The answer is simple: for far too long our species has become complacent with the status quo. Since WW2, we have been "petal to the metal", exploiting as much as possible as rapidly as possible to get our grubby hands on as many "shiny things" as we possibly could. Our species has taken zero measures to "slow down" our status quo, and literally every single decision that has been collectively made over the past 150 years was designed to maximize the status quo.

How much longer can the Charade continue before BAU grinds to a halt ? Only Time will tell, but I for one, will wish COVID-19 well and congratulate it on its future success.

This is famous picture of Our Lady of Guadalupe
Let's take a closer look
A bit of context: Guadalupe is most likely Spanish trying to write Nahualt word 'coatlaxopueh' = "the one who tramples the snake"
A young Indian man had a vision of Mary and she told him to gather flowers in his garment, he found the flowers though they didn't bloom in that time of year and brought them to the priest. When he unraveled the garment the picture was on it.
On the picture Mary is shown without a mask, in Aztec art deities were drawn with masks, showing she isn't a deity, yet she stands upon the moon (deity in Aztec religion) and is clothed in stars
A woman higher than deities?
Mary has a black cloth tied around belly, in Aztec culture it signified pregnancy, yet she has her hair loose: symbol of virginity
A pregnant virgin?
On her dress, in the place uterus is, she has four-petal flower
This flower was in Aztec culture symbol of complete perfection, highest divinity
A pregnant virgin carrying the God, Lord of Universe in her womb?
Aditionally in that region they make the clothes of material that gets easily destroyed with time

Ah salvia... Remember those shitty 80s and 90s movies where some fucker smokes weed and sees Mickey mouse, or some other hallucination? Complete bullshit, right? No, salvia will take you into another world. I've done it a handful of times, and I was the only person in my group of friends that enjoyed it.
It hits like Russian roulette. The first few hits might do nothing, but it will hit you like a sack of bricks when it does. You will enter a whole new reality and you will become something else. My first experience, I was at a friend's place. When it hit me, I immediately when into a dreamlike state, in which I was a sun flower...but I was incomplete. I looked up, and the missing petal floated down from the sky and attached to me. I felt like I became perfect in that moment and was extremely relaxed and content the rest of the night.
Another experience: after smoking it with friends, I woke up in an orange grove in Italy. I was a wooden wheel rolling through the countryside as the sun was setting. It was extremely peaceful.
The experience lasts like 10 minutes and is the trippiest shit I've ever experienced.

Do not rhyme with here but ere.
Seven is right, but so is even,
Hyphen, roughen, nephew Stephen,
Monkey, donkey, Turk and jerk,
Ask, grasp, wasp, and cork and work.

Pronunciation -- think of Psyche!
Is a paling stout and spikey?
Won't it make you lose your wits,
Writing groats and saying grits?
It's a dark abyss or tunnel:
Strewn with stones, stowed, solace, gunwale,
Islington and Isle of Wight,
Housewife, verdict and indict.

comments:
any of a family (Coronaviridae) of large single-stranded RNA viruses that have a lipid envelope studded with club-shaped spike proteins, infect birds and many mammals including humans, and include the causative agents of MERS, SARS, and COVID-19 Coronaviruses can cause a variety of illnesses in animals, but in people coronaviruses cause one-third of common colds and sometimes respiratory infections in premature infants.

The word was introduced by a group of virologists as a short article "Coronaviruses" in the "News and Views" section of Nature (vol. 220, no. 5168, November 16, 1968, p. 650): "… avian infectious bronchitis virus has a characteristic electron microscopic appearance resembling, but distinct from, that of myxoviruses. Particles are more or less rounded in profile … there is also a characteristic 'fringe' of projections 200 Å long, which are rounded or petal shaped, rather than sharp or pointed, as in the myxoviruses. This appearance, recalling the solar corona, is shared by mouse hepatitis virus … . In the opinion of the eight virologists these viruses are members of a previously unrecognized group which they suggest should be called the coronaviruses, to recall the characteristic appearance by which these viruses are identified in the electron microscope."

Honestly, anon, if you bother to research this, you'll find that HCQ is literally useless for Covid. See, for example:

https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2772921

>This issue of JAMA contains yet another study, and certainly among the best published to date, demonstrating the lack of efficacy of hydroxychloroquine as a treatment of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19). This study, from the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute PETAL Clinical Trials Network, focused on hospitalized patients with moderate to severe disease. In this well-conducted, appropriately powered clinical trial, the authors randomized 479 patients to receive hydroxychloroquine (400 mg twice daily for 2 doses, then 200 mg twice daily for 8 doses) (n=242) or placebo (n=237). The trial was stopped early at the fourth interim analysis for futility. For the primary outcome, clinical status at 14 days measured on a 7-category ordinal scale, there was no significant difference between the hydroxychloroquine and placebo groups (median [interquartile range {IQR}] score, 6 [4-7] vs 6 [4-7]; adjusted odds ratio, 1.02 [95% CI, 0.73-1.42]). None of the 12 secondary outcomes were significantly different between groups, including mortality at 28 days: 10.4% in the hydroxychloroquine group vs 10.6% in the placebo group (absolute difference, −0.2% [95% CI, −5.7% to 5.3%]; adjusted odds ratio, 1.07 [95% CI, 0.54 to 2.09]). Thus, the results conclusively show no benefit of hydroxychloroquine over placebo.

Do your research, anon.

comments:
Not in .22 LR, against human targets, except possibly if you can only get round-nose and you know you're firing out of rifle-length barrel at close range. You can buy hollow points (designed to expand) and segmented (designed to split apart) .22 LR ammo off the shelf.

Segmented is good for varmints, greatly reducing penetration depth (which you don't need as much of in a small animal), in exchange for cutting multiple wound tracks, making a badly-placed shot more likely to be fatal anyway. Hollow point is designed for controlled expansion, which does enhance the terminal effect, provided the bullet is going fast enough for the impact to cause the expansion to happen, and the bullet can still penetrate deeply enough after expanding.

Out of a pistol, .22 hollow point won't expand (because it's going slower and so doesn't slap the target as fiercely), and you wouldn't want it to. You're struggling to get enough penetration depth. A half-assed modification of a bullet to try and make it expand more like cutting a cross on the tip is probably going to make it unstable in flight, and might screw up its ability to penetrate sufficiently.

Usually a "flower petal" bullet is jacketed, with the copper jacket holding the bullet together as the petals fold out. Lead is a much weaker metal, and .22 LR bullets don't have copper jackets (though they sometimes have a very thin "copper wash"), so trying to recreate the same effect probably makes bullets that break apart into smaller pieces that don't get very far into the target.
